"PORE: Provably Robust Recommender Systems against Data Poisoning Attacks.","3","[47] Sheng Zhang, Amit Chakrabarti, James Ford, and Fillia Makedon. Attack detection in time series for recom-mender systems. In KDD, 2006. A Proof of Theorem 3.1 Recall that, given a rating-score matrix M and its poisoned version M′, X and Y are respectively two submatrices with s rows randomly sampled from M and M′ without replacement. We use Φ to denote the domain space of Y , i.e., each element in Φ is a submatrix with s rows sampled from M′. Note that since M is a submatrix of M′, the domain space of X is a subset of Φ. For simplicity, we define the following notations. Suppose we have Z ∈Φ and another rating-score matrix W , we say Z ≺W (or Z ⊀W ) if Z is (or is not) in the domain space created by sampling s rows from W . We have X ≺M and Y ≺M′ based on our defined notations. Similarly, give a user u and Z ∈Φ, we say u ⊢Z if Z contains rating scores of user u. We say u ⊬Z if Z does not contain user u’s rating scores. The following lemma generalizes the Neyman-Pearson Lemma"
