unctions, we have the following probabilities: Pr(X ∈P) = 1− (︃n−1 s )︃ · 1 (︁n s )︁= s n, Pr(X ∈A) = s n, (26) Pr(Y ∈P) = s n · (︁n s )︁ (︁n′ s )︁, Pr(Y ∈A) = s n′ . (27) We have Pr(X /∈P) = (︁n−1 s )︁ · 1 (n s) because there are overall (︁n−1 s )︁ possible submatrices if the user u is not sampled from M. Then, we can compute Pr(X ∈P) based on the fact that Pr(X ∈P)+Pr(X /∈P) ="
"PORE: Provably Robust Recommender Systems against Data Poisoning Attacks.","3","1. We obtain Pr(X ∈A) based on the fact that P ⊆A and A∩B = /0. Similarly, we can compute the probability of Y in these subsets. We will leverage the law of contraposition to prove our theorem. Suppose we have a statement: U −→V, then, its contraposition is ¬V −→¬U. The law of contraposition tells us that a statement is true if and only if its contraposition is true. We define the following two predicates: U : p∗ µr > min( N−r+1 min c=1 N′ ·(p∗ Hc +σ) c , p∗ v1 +σ) (28) and 1 ≤r ≤min(k,N), V : |Iu ∩T (M′,u)| ≥r, (29) where σ = s n′ · (n′ s) (n s) −s n . Deriving the necessary condition: We assume ¬V is true, i.e., |Iu ∩T (M′,u)| < r. If r = 0 or r > min(k,N), then, ¬U is true. Next, we consider 1 ≤r ≤min(k,N) and we will show p∗ µr ≤min(minN−r+1 c=1 N′·(p∗ Hc+σ) c , p∗ v1 +σ) is true. If |Iu∩ T (M′,u)| < r, then, there exist at least k −r + 1 items in Iu that are not recommended to the user u by our ensemble recommender system when taking M′ as input. In other words, there exist at least N −r + 1 items in I \\ Iu appears in the recommended item set T (M′,u). For simplicity, we use Dr and Vr to denote subsets of k−r+1 items in Iu and N −r+1 items in I \\Iu, respectively. Formally, we have the following: ∃Dr,Vr, s.t. Dr ∩T (M′,u) = /0,Vr ⊆T (M′,u), (30) The above equation means that the poisoned item probabilities of the items in Vr are no smaller than the poisoned item probabilities of the items in Dr. In other words, we have the following for Dr and Vr: max i∈Dr Pr(i ∈A(Y ,u)) ≤min j∈Vr Pr(j ∈A(Y ,u)). (31) Moreover, since there exist Dr and Vr, we have the follow-ing necessary condition if |Iu ∩T (M′,u)| < r and 1 ≤r ≤ min(k,N): min Dr max i∈Dr Pr(i ∈A(Y ,u)) ≤max Vr min j∈Vr Pr(j ∈A(Y ,u)). (32) Next, we will derive the lower bound of left-hand side and the upper bound of the right-hand side for the above equation. Deriving a lower bound of minDr maxi∈Dr Pr(i ∈ A(Y ,u)): For ∀i ∈Dr, based on Equation (3), we have the following: p∗ i ≜⌊pi · (︁n s )︁ ⌋ (︁n s )︁ ≤pi ≤Pr(i ∈A(X,u)) (33) Based on the definition of X, we have: Pr(i ∈A(X,u)) ≥p∗ i . (34) For ∀i ∈Dr, we define the function gi(Z) = I(i ∈A(Z,u)), where I is an indicator function. Specifically, we have gi(Z) = 0 for ∀Z ∈B based on the definition of B in Equation (23), which will be used when we leverage Lemma 1 to derive the lower bound of Pr(gi(Y ) = 1). We have Pr(gi(X) = 1) ≥p∗ i based on Equation (34) and the definition of gi. For ∀i ∈Dr, we can find Ci ⊆P such that we have the following: Pr(X ∈Ci) = p∗ i . (35) Note that we can find such a subset because p∗ i is an integer multiple of 1 (n s). Then, we have the following: Pr(gi(X) = 1) ≥Pr(X ∈Ci). (36) For simplicity, we define the following quantity: τ = (︃n s )︃ / (︃n′ s )︃ . (37) Next, we will apply Lemma 1 to obtain the lower bound of Pr(gi(Y ) = 1). In particular, we let Φ′ = B since we have gi(Z) = 0 for ∀Z ∈B. Note that we omit Q since we have Q ⊆B. Then, we have A = Φ\\Φ′. Based on Equation (24) - (25), we have Pr(Y = Z) = τ·Pr(X = Z) if Z ∈P and Pr(Y = 1718    32nd USENIX Security Symposium USENIX Association Z) > τ·Pr(X = Z) if Z ∈A\\P. We let O1 = /0 since there is no subset that satisfies Pr(Y = Z) < τ·Pr(X = Z). Furthermore, we let O2 = P, O3 = Ci ⊆O2, η = 1, and γ ="
"PORE: Provably Robust Recommender Systems against Data Poisoning Attacks.","3","1. Finally, we let O = O1 ∪O3 = Ci. We can apply Lemma 1 based on the condition in Equation (36) and we have the following: Pr(gi(Y ) = 1) ≥Pr(Y ∈Ci). (38) Based on the definition of gi, we have the following: Pr(i ∈A(Y ,u)) (39) =Pr(gi(Y ) = 1) (40) ≥Pr(Y ∈Ci) (41) =Pr(X ∈Ci)·τ (42) =p∗ i ·τ. (43) For simplicity, we denote Dr = {d′ 1,d′ 2,··· ,d′ z}, where z = k −r +1. Without loss of generality, we assume pd′ 1 ≥··· ≥ pd′z. We have the following: max i∈Dr Pr(i ∈A(Y ,u)) ≥max i∈Dr p∗ i ·τ = p∗ d′ 1 ·τ. (44) Then, we have the following: min Dr max i∈Dr Pr(i ∈A(Y ,u)) = min Dr p∗ d′ 1 ·τ (45) Therefore, when Dr = {µr,µr+1,··· ,µk}, p∗ d′ 1 ·τ reaches the minimal value which is p∗ µr ·τ. In other words, we have the following: min Dr max i∈Dr Pr(i ∈A(Y ,u)) ≥p∗ µr ·τ. (46) Deriving an upper bound of maxVr min j∈Vr Pr(j ∈ A(Y ,u)): For ∀j ∈Vr, given Equation (3), we have the fol-lowing: p∗ j = ⌈pj · (︁n s )︁ ⌉ (︁n s )︁ ≥pj ≥Pr(j ∈A(X,u)). (47) Suppose we have Vr = {v′ 1,v′ 2,··· ,v′ w}, where w = N −r+1. Without loss of generality, we assume the following: pv′ 1 ≤pv′ 2 ≤··· ≤pv′w. (48) We first derive an upper bound of minj∈Vr Pr(j ∈A(Y ,u)). Given an arbitrary item j ∈Vr, we have the following inequal-ity based on Equation (47) and our definition of X: Pr(j ∈A(X,u)) ≤p∗ j. (49) Given an item j ∈Vr, we define the function gj(Z) = I(j ∈ A(Z,u)). We have Pr(gj(X) = 1) ≤p∗ j based on Equa-tion (49) and the definition of gj. Then, we can leverage Lemma 1 to derive an upper bound for Pr(gj(X) = 1). In par-ticular, we can find C′ j ⊆P such that we have the following: Pr(X ∈C′ j) = p∗ j. (50) We let Cj = C′ j ∪(A \\ P). Since we have Pr(X ∈A \\ P) = Pr(X ∈A)−Pr(X ∈P) = 0, we have the following: Pr(X ∈Cj) = Pr(X ∈C′ j)+Pr(X ∈A\\P) = p∗ j. (51) Based on Pr(g j(X) = 1) ≤p∗ j, we have the following: Pr(gj(X) = 1) ≤Pr(X ∈Cj). (52) Next, we will apply Lemma 1 to obtain the upper bound of Pr(gj(Y) = 1). In particular, we let Φ′ = B since we have gj(Z) = 0 for ∀Z ∈B. Then, we have A = Φ\\Φ′. Based on Equation (24) - (25), we have Pr(Y = Z) = τ·Pr(X = Z) if Z ∈P and Pr(Y = Z) > τ · Pr(X = Z) if Z ∈A \\ P. We let O1 = A\\P, O2 = P, O3 = C′ j ⊆O2, η = 1, and γ ="
