"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","[32] Peter Williams, Radu Sion, and Bogdan Carbunar. Building Castles out of Mud: Practical Access Pattern Privacy and Correctness on Untrusted Storage. In CCS, pages 139–148, 2008."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","[33] Samee Zahur, Xiao Wang, Mariana Raykova, Adrià Gascón, Jack Doerner, David Evans, and Jonathan Katz. Revisiting Square-Root ORAM: Efﬁcient Random Ac-cess in Multi-party Computation. In IEEE Symposium on Security and Privacy, pages 218–234, 2016. A Generating AND and Dot-Product Triples This section presents two methods to generate the multipli-cation triples that were discussed in Section 2.2.1. We use XOR-shared AND triples in the 2-party and 3-party READ and UPDATE preprocessing protocols. Using a third party. Here, a stateless third party (which does not collude with either other party) samples the 5-tuple (X0,X1,Y0,Y1,T) uniformly and sends the AND triples (X0,Y0,(X0 ∧Y1) ⊕T) and (X1,Y1,(X1 ∧Y0) ⊕T) to P0 and P1 respectively. This process of generating AND triples using a noncolluding third party results in a protocol called the Du– Atallah protocol [9]. Du–Atallah’s multiplication protocol is a variant of the more celebrated Beaver triples protocol, where we replace the OT with a third party. Using Oblivious Transfer. The Du–Atallah triples used in MPC bitwise multiplication can be generated without the third party by using Oblivious Transfer with the following protocol:"
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","1. P0 picks (X0,Y0) at random from {0,1}w and P1 picks (X1,Y1) at random from {0,1}w."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","2. P0 and P1 pick random words T0 ∈{0,1}w and T1 ∈ {0,1}w respectively. Let T = T0 ⊕T1."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","3. P0 acts as the sender in w parallel 1-of-2 oblivious trans-fers with the ith bits of (T0,X0 ⊕T0) as the input. P1 uses the bits of Y1 as the selection bits. Therefore, P1 learns (X0 ∧Y1)⊕T0 and computes (X0 ∧Y1)⊕T0 ⊕T1 = (X0 ∧Y1)⊕T."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","4. In parallel, P1 acts as a sender with the words (T1,X1 ⊕ T1), and P0 uses Y0 as the selection word, so P0 learns (X1 ∧Y0)⊕T1 and computes (X1 ∧Y0)⊕T1 ⊕T0 = (X1 ∧ Y0)⊕T. B Proofs of DUORAM Operations This section presents the correctness proofs of various DUO-RAM protocols. We will begin this section by proving the correctness of the READ protocol. Proof of Lemma 1. read0 +read1 = ⟨D0 + eD1,t (1) 0 ⟩−⟨ζ0,t (3) 0 −t (1) 0 ⟩+γ0 +⟨D1 + eD0,t (1) 1 ⟩−⟨ζ1,t (2) 1 −t (1) 1 ⟩+γ1 = ⟨D0 +(D1 +ζ1),t (1) 0 ⟩−⟨ζ0,t (3) 0 −t (1) 0 ⟩+γ0 +⟨D1 +(D0 +ζ0),t (1) 1 ⟩−⟨ζ1,t (2) 1 −t (1) 1 ⟩+γ1 = ⟨D,t (1) 0 ⟩+⟨ζ1,t (1) 0 ⟩−⟨ζ0,(t (3) 0 −t (1) 0 )⟩+γ0 +⟨D,t (1) 1 ⟩+⟨ζ0,t (1) 1 ⟩−⟨ζ1,(t (2) 1 −t (1) 1 )⟩+γ1 = ⟨D,ei∗⟩+⟨ζ1,ei∗⟩+⟨ζ0,ei∗⟩ −⟨ζ0,t (3) 0 ⟩−⟨ζ1,t (2) 1 ⟩+γ0 +γ1 = ⟨D,ei∗⟩+⟨ζ1,ei∗⟩+⟨ζ0,ei∗⟩ −⟨ζ0,t (3) 0 ⟩−⟨ζ1,t (2) 1 ⟩−⟨ζ0,t (3) 1 ⟩−⟨ζ1,t (2) 0 ⟩ = ⟨D,ei∗⟩+⟨ζ1,ei∗⟩+⟨ζ0,ei∗⟩−⟨ζ1,ei∗⟩−⟨ζ0,ei∗⟩ = ⟨D,ei∗⟩ Next, we will prove the correctness of the REFRESH-BLINDS protocol. Proof of Lemma 3. eD′ 0 = f D0 +v (2) 1 −v (1) 1 = (D0 +ζ0)+v (2) 1 −v (1) 1 = (D0 +ζ0)+(M·ei∗−v (2) 0 )−(M·ei∗−v (1) 0 ) = (D0 +v (1) 0 )+(ζ0 −v (2) 0 ) = (D′ 0 +ζ′ 0) and similarly for eD′ 1. Finally, we will prove the correctness of the 2P-DUORAM READ protocol. USENIX Association 32nd USENIX Security Symposium    3923 Proof of Lemma 4. read0 +read1 = c0 −r0 +c1 −r1 = D1[i∗]+r1 −r0 +D0[i∗]+r0 −r1 = D1[i∗]+D0[i∗] = D[ i∗] C DPF Generation Algorithm The following protocol is the DPF generation presented in the FLORAM paper by Doerner and shelat [8]. Suppose that we want to create DPF at the target location, i∗. Represent i∗as a binary bit vector ⃗i∗. The parties P0 and P1 start with XOR shares ⃗i∗ 0 and ⃗i∗ 1 of ⃗i∗, and create random seeds v ( ) 0 ∈{0,1}λ and v ( ) 1 ∈{0,1}λ respectively to use as the roots of binary trees. They use a length-doubling PRG to construct the remainder of the trees, as outlined below. We denote by vb,ℓthe nodes at level ℓ, and by tb,ℓthe ﬂags at level ℓ, both in the tree share held by Pb. We ﬁrst set the least signiﬁcant bit (lsb) of Pb’s root as b; i.e. set lsb(v ( ) 0 ) ←0 and lsb(v ( ) 1 ) ←1. Set t0,0[0] ←lsb(v ( ) 0 ) and t1,0[0] ←lsb(v ( ) 1 ). For each layer ℓstarting at the root with ℓ= 0:"
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","1. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb uses the PRG to construct the labels on the children of each node in this level. The left and right children of node i at this layer are denoted as (v (i∥L) b,ℓ,v (i∥R) b,ℓ). Therefore, we have vb,ℓ+1[2·i] = v (i∥L) b,ℓand vb,ℓ+1[2·i + 1] = v (i∥R) b,ℓ."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","2. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb computes Lb ←L2ℓ−1 j=0 v (j∥L) b,ℓand Rb ← L2ℓ−1 j=0 v (j∥R) b,ℓ."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","3. P0 and P1 use an MPC AND protocol (using the AND triple generation described in Ap-pendix A) to compute the correction word cw (ℓ+1) ←  ⃗i∗ 0[ℓ]⊕⃗i∗ 1[ℓ]  ∧(L0 ⊕L1)  ⊕  1⊕⃗i∗ 0[ℓ]⊕⃗i∗ 1[ℓ]  ∧(R0 ⊕R1)  ."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","4. Pb computes cwtb L ←lsb(Lb) ⊕⃗i∗ b[ℓ] and cwtb R ← lsb(Rb) ⊕⃗i∗ b[ℓ], and exchanges those values with the other party; the parties then both compute cwtL ← cwt0 L ⊕cwt1 L ⊕1 and cwtR ←cwt0 R ⊕cwt1 R."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","5. Pb computes tb,ℓ+1[2 · i] ←lsb(vb,ℓ+1[2 · i]) ⊕(tb,ℓ[i] · cwtL) and tb,ℓ+1[2 · i + 1] ←lsb(vb,ℓ+1[2 · i + 1]) ⊕ (tb,ℓ[i]· cwtR), for all i ∈[0,2ℓ)."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","6. Pb updates vb,ℓ+1[2·i] ←vb,ℓ+1[2·i]⊕(tb,ℓ[i]·cw (ℓ+1)) and vb,ℓ+1[2·i+1] ←vb,ℓ+1[2·i+1]⊕(tb,ℓ[i]·cw (ℓ+1)), for all i ∈[0,2ℓ). D Converting an XOR-shared standard basis vector to additive shares In this section, we elaborate upon the informal description of the share conversion algorithm described in Section 4.1.1. Recall that P0 and P1 hold DPFs without the ﬁnal correction word; that is, P0 holds (v0,˚t0,F0) and P1 holds (v1,˚t1,F1) such that ˚t0 ⊕˚t1 = eri and v0 +v1 = −(F0 +F1)·eri. Their goal is to end up with vectors t0 and t1 such that t0 +t1 = eri. An important point to note is that, in this case, ˚tb and the pair (vb,Fb) are not of the same DPF (but have the same target index). In other words, we use an additional DPF to perform the share conversion."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","1. P0 interprets its ﬂag vector as a word vector. P1 also interprets its ﬂag vector as a word vector and multiplies it by −1. In other words, P0 computes bt0[i] ←(˚t0[i]) for all i, and P1 computesbt1[i] ←−(˚t1[i]) for all i."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","2. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb computes pmb ←∑ibtb[i]."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","3. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb selects a random word rb to blind pmb, and the Pb exchange pmb +rb."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","4. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb updates bt′ b ←btb · ((pm1−b + r1−b) + pmb +rb)."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","5. The parties use MPC to compute shares eF0 and eF1 of (F0 +F1)·(pm0 +pm1)."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","6. The parties then compute F ′ 0 ←eF0 +r0 and F ′ 1 ←eF1 + r1 respectively, and exchange them to reconstruct F ′ ← F ′ 0 +F ′ 1."
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","7. For b ∈{0,1}, Pb updates tb ←bt′ b −vb −(btb ·F ′). Lemma"
"Duoram: A Bandwidth-Efficient Distributed ORAM for 2- and 3-Party Computation.","1","5. After running the above protocol, t0 +t1 = ˚t0 ⊕ ˚t1 = eri. Proof. Denote pm = pm0 +pm1. First observe that bt0[i]+ bt1[i] = 0 for i ̸= ri, so pm = bt0[ri] +bt1[ri] = ˚t0[ri] − ˚t1[ri], which is either +1 or −1, and so pm2 is always 1. Also note thatbt0 +bt1 = pm·eri. Let r = r0 +r1, F = F0 +F1, eF = eF0 + eF1. Then bt′ b = btb · (pm + r), so bt′ 0 + bt′ 1 = (pm · eri) · (pm + r) = eri · (1 + pm · r). Also eF = F · pm, and F ′ = eF + r = F · pm + r. Finally, recall that v0 + v1 = −F · eri, so that t0 + t1 = (bt′ 0 +bt′ 1) −(v0 + v1) − (bt0 + bt1) · F ′ = eri · ␀(1+pm·r)+F −pm·F ′ = eri · ((1+pm·r)+F −pm·(F ·pm+r)) = eri. 3924    32nd USENIX Security Symposium USENIX Association"
